<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="448" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1791,2023]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,1792,1815]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[391,495,1791,1815]" class="Arachnida" family="Zoridae" genus="Hoedillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[391,495,1791,1815]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="447">Hoedillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the following combination of characters: (
<number box="[1160,1171,1792,1815]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="1.0">1</number>
) eight eyes forming two strongly recurved rows, (
<number box="[426,440,1826,1849]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="2.0">2</number>
) lateral eyes of both rows 
<number box="[740,773,1826,1849]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times the diameter of median eyes, (
<docIssue box="[1186,1199,1826,1849]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447">
<number box="[1186,1199,1826,1849]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="3.0">3</number>
</docIssue>
) four to five pairs of ventral spines in raised sockets on tibia I and II, and two pairs of ventral spines in raised sockets on metatarsi I and II, and (
<number box="[159,174,1896,1919]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="4.0">4</number>
) three promarginal and two retromarginal cheliceral teeth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1791,2023]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="448" pageId="0" pageNumber="447">
<emphasis box="[199,465,1929,1953]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="447">Justification of transfer.</emphasis>
An examination of the male pedipalpus fails to reveal synapomorphic characters for 
<taxonomicName box="[151,269,1965,1988]" class="Arachnida" family="Miturgidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Miturgidae</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[286,345,1965,1988]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="447">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez" box="[354,512,1965,1988]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" refString="Ramirez, M. J. (2014) The morphology and phylogeny of the dionychan spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 390, 1 - 374. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 821.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Ramírez 
<number box="[453,512,1965,1988]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
): a retrolateral cymbial groove (
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" refString="Ramirez, M. J. (2014) The morphology and phylogeny of the dionychan spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 390, 1 - 374. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 821.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Ramírez 
<number box="[962,1019,1965,1988]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="2014.0">2014</number>
: figs. 
<number box="[1087,1126,1965,1988]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="145.0">145</number>
F, 
<number box="[1155,1196,1965,1988]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="148.0">148</number>
D, 
<number box="[1229,1270,1965,1988]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="162.0">162</number>
A, B; character 
<number box="[151,194,2000,2023]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="331.0">331</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), retrolateral tibial apophysis (RTA) with membranous area (
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez" box="[846,1393,2000,2023]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" refString="Ramirez, M. J. (2014) The morphology and phylogeny of the dionychan spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 390, 1 - 374. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 821.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Ramírez 
<number box="[945,1002,2000,2023]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="2014.0">2014</number>
: figs. 
<number box="[1067,1108,2000,2023]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="145.0">145</number>
A, 
<number box="[1140,1180,2000,2023]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="163.0">163</number>
A, B; character 
<number box="[1350,1393,2000,2023]" pageId="0" pageNumber="447" value="315.0">315</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), or a canal on the RTA (
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez" box="[375,997,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" refString="Ramirez, M. J. (2014) The morphology and phylogeny of the dionychan spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 390, 1 - 374. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 821.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Ramírez 
<number box="[475,532,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="2014.0">2014</number>
: figs. 
<number box="[599,640,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="142.0">142</number>
E, 
<number box="[670,712,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="146.0">146</number>
B, 
<number box="[742,783,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="160.0">160</number>
E, H; character 
<number box="[953,997,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="316.0">316</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, the shape of the embolus and median apophysis is inconsistent with this group; 
<taxonomicName box="[745,849,185,209]" class="Arachnida" family="Zoridae" genus="Hoedillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[745,849,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="448">Hoedillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks the long circular embolus and a forward facing median apophysis seen in the 
<taxonomicName box="[475,593,221,244]" class="Arachnida" family="Miturgidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Miturgidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez" box="[608,928,221,244]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" refString="Ramirez, M. J. (2014) The morphology and phylogeny of the dionychan spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 390, 1 - 374. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 821.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Ramírez 
<number box="[708,765,221,244]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="2014.0">2014</number>
: figs. 
<number box="[830,928,221,244]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="145146.0">145, 146</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The examination also fails to reveal a tegular division (
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez" box="[251,407,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" refString="Ramirez, M. J. (2014) The morphology and phylogeny of the dionychan spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 390, 1 - 374. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 821.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Ramírez 
<number box="[350,407,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 
<number box="[472,512,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="150.0">150</number>
A–C, E; character 
<number box="[712,752,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="343.0">343</number>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Silva" box="[805,924,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" refString="Silva, D. (2003) Higher-level relationships of the spider family Ctenidae (Araneae: Ctenoidea). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 274, 1 - 86. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2003) 274 &lt;0001: HLROTS&gt; 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2003">
Silva 
<number box="[867,924,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 
<number box="[978,1007,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="18.0">18</number>
; character 
<number box="[1124,1153,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="38.0">38</number>
), which is synapomorphic for the 
<taxonomicName box="[228,351,290,313]" class="Arachnida" family="Zoridae" genus="Xenoctenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[228,351,290,313]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="448">Xenoctenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448">
Both males and females of 
<taxonomicName box="[494,597,324,348]" class="Arachnida" family="Zoridae" genus="Hoedillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[494,597,324,348]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="448">Hoedillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show characters previously considered as synapomorphies of 
<taxonomicName box="[1268,1392,325,348]" class="Arachnida" family="Zoropsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Zoropsidae</taxonomicName>
: the lateral eyes are larger than the median eyes (
<figureCitation box="[625,685,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,244,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[223,1348,199,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[212,1360,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hoedillus sexpunctatus Simon, 1898, male. A. Habitus. B – F. Right pedipalpus; B. Retrolateral view; C. Ventral view; D. Prolateral view; E. Tibia ventral view; F. Pedipalpus, dorsal view, highlighting dorsal cymbial scopula. Con—conductor, Em—embolus, MA—median apophysis, TA—tegular apophysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262395/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="448">
Fig. 
<number box="[675,685,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<bibRefCitation author="Raven" box="[721,976,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" refString="Raven, R. J. &amp; Stumkat, K. S. (2005) Revisions of Australian ground-hunting spiders: II. Zoropsidae (Lycosoidea: Araneae). Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 50, 347 - 423." type="journal article" year="2005">
Raven &amp; Stumkat 
<number box="[919,976,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: character 
<number box="[1091,1122,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="42.0">42</number>
). The male pedipalpus shows dense dorsal cymbial scopula with flattened surface (
<figureCitation box="[719,772,394,417]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,244,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[223,1348,199,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[212,1360,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hoedillus sexpunctatus Simon, 1898, male. A. Habitus. B – F. Right pedipalpus; B. Retrolateral view; C. Ventral view; D. Prolateral view; E. Tibia ventral view; F. Pedipalpus, dorsal view, highlighting dorsal cymbial scopula. Con—conductor, Em—embolus, MA—median apophysis, TA—tegular apophysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262395/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="448">
Fig 
<number box="[763,772,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B–D, F; 
<bibRefCitation author="Raven" box="[870,1126,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" refString="Raven, R. J. &amp; Stumkat, K. S. (2005) Revisions of Australian ground-hunting spiders: II. Zoropsidae (Lycosoidea: Araneae). Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 50, 347 - 423." type="journal article" year="2005">
Raven &amp; Stumkat 
<number box="[1069,1126,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: character 
<number box="[1241,1253,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="1.0">1</number>
), and the female is found to have dorsal spigots on the posterior median spinnerets (
<bibRefCitation author="Raven" box="[921,1348,429,452]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" refString="Raven, R. J. &amp; Stumkat, K. S. (2005) Revisions of Australian ground-hunting spiders: II. Zoropsidae (Lycosoidea: Araneae). Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 50, 347 - 423." type="journal article" year="2005">
Raven &amp; Stumkat 
<number box="[1136,1193,429,452]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="2005.0">2005</number>
: character 
<number box="[1318,1348,429,452]" pageId="1" pageNumber="448" value="63.0">63</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). These characters justify its placement in this family.
</paragraph>
